<p>Would you mind elaborating this very specific message?</p>
<p>I also agree with Nederbörd regarding the depiction of Nazis, and as Rabe said the use of German words seems rather random and could easily be seen like a style element intended to use German language as means to make it look more Nazi-like which is a use of our language most of us would find very, very disrespectful so I just assume that was not your intention.</p>
<p>As the Obskurakorps (Korps is written with k in German) is meant to be part of the SS, I suggest using <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparative_ranks_of_Nazi_Germany">SS ranks</a>, e.g. &quot;SS-Untersturmführer&quot; instead of &quot;Lieutenant&quot; or the respective rank instead of &quot;commander&quot;.</p>
<p>To further elaborate the problem Rabe, I and lots of DE users have with this kind of depiction of Nazis is, that it not only is very historically inaccurate, it is depicting them as mindless villains. As monsters. But they where not. None of them intended to do evil. Instead they did what they thought was necessary. Nobody depicts US soldiers burning vietnamese children alive as mindless monsters I think. Or the british pilots bombing German cities to kill civilians.<br />
They where humans, nothing more. They where following orders, given by people who where also following orders. Some because they stopped thinking, some because they thought it was necessary, some because they where afraid, some because they where indoctrinated by hate. All they did lies in the capacity of human mind. Dehumanizing them also dehumanizes their victims. It lets them look like the victims of an inevitable evil. Like something extraordinary. Something uniquely bad. But it wasn't. Inhumane crimes of all sorts and all scales have been done before, during and after the war, by lots of countries including the US. Some are still doing horrible crimes against humanity today and are not even a bit ashamed of it.<br />
This picture of Nazis that is common in US media is basically WW2 propaganda. It was meant to reach the people on an emotional level, without having to explain much and thereby entertaining the people to keep their attention and to appeal to their patriotism. Though I understand that is what works to depict Nazis in the US.<br />
I guess our attempt would be highly controversial in the US. We'll see when more of our SKP-articles are available in the INT. I would favor if we could find ways to make articles compatible to both ways to depict Nazis in the future and I'm open for discussions thereabout.</p>

							</div>

