			<div class="content" id="post-content-3870185">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Nobody depicts US soldiers burning vietnamese children alive as mindless monsters I think.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You seem to be unfamiliar with the anti-war movement in the US, then. Also I imagine Vietnamese propaganda did so.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>All they did lies in the capacity of human mind. Dehumanizing them also dehumanizes their victims. It lets them look like the victims of an inevitable evil. Like something extraordinary. Something uniquely bad. But it wasn't.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&quot;Once upon a time there was a people who believed in Santa Claus, until they discovered Santa Claus was the gas man.&quot;</p>
<p>Yes, I am very sensitive to the concept of the mundanity of evil. I hope to address some of your concerns with my long delayed entry into this series. Trying to humanize Obskura's final hours while maintaining continuity and tone is one of the obstacles I have been struggling with, frankly.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Inhumane crimes of all sorts and all scales have been done before, during and after the war, by lots of countries including the US. Some are still doing horrible crimes against humanity today and are not even a bit ashamed of it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yes, to some extent. However, I think it is important to recognize that the kind of systematic industrialized genocide of the Final Solution as well as the way that the Nazi Party deliberately weaponized racial identity politics are the particular 20th century horrific innovations of the 3rd Reich. It doesn't deserve a pass for this just because other states have engaged in atrocities of various scales, before and since.</p>

							</div>

								
