<blockquote>
<p>I personally do not think that such crimes can be valued anyhow. Those tortured to death are tortured to death. It doesn't get any worse for them because their murderers are Nazis, Sovjets, CIA or some mafia thugs. Valueing their deaths serves only the living.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The point is, that when the enemy develops a weapon, you take note of its signs so that you can recognize and counter it before it is deployed again. While, yes, the same thing is true of chattel slavery or forced cultural assimilation, and many others, the signs of these weapons of the enemy are different, as are their counters.</p>
<p>The enemy invented factory genocide and weaponized racial identity politics in the 1940s and 30s respectively, and we would be foolish to not take note that these are now within the arsenal. Rwanda might have been different had the people who recognized weaponized identity at the time been willing and able to intervene.</p>
<p>One sees the signs of the latter all over, these days, I'm afraid.</p>

