<p>I honestly don't know where you're getting &quot;mindless villains&quot; or &quot;mindless monsters&quot; in the context of this article from. While that is definitely a problem in media in general, it just isn't the case for this particular piece. The story this tells is of some highly competent scientists (as occultism in the SCP universe is just another form of science) trying to achieve a very specific goal in accordance to their ideologies. I really can't see where this fits into the notion of mindless villains, they are trying to use every means at their disposal to win the war, which in the SCP universe includes occult methods. That is something that is in no way limited to the Nazis within this universe, as the rest of this series and countless other articles show, occultism is utilized by pretty much every major organisation, political or otherwise. Consequently, the Third Reich is no exception.<br />
The argument that all of them were following orders also doesn't track. Yes, for a lot of people that were involved with the atrocities commited during the era this is true. Nobody is pretending otherwise. But that was not the case for everyone. Plenty of people agreed very much with the Nazi ideology. Orders have to be given by someone, fear as to be spread by someone, indoctrination and spreading of hate has to be performed by people. They don't exist in a vacuum, some of the people involved were, by our standards, very much evil and saying everyone involved was just following orders in some form or other is frankly more insulting to the victims of the Nazi regime than any attempt at dehumanizing could be. And even if that wasn't the case, this article does not in any way attempt to dehumanize the Nazis. On the contrary, it makes a point of clearly laying out what their motivations for doing what they attempt to do are, instead of pretending they do it &quot;because they're evil&quot;.</p>

